Splitting a data container into subsets

Until now, we’ve only created a single data container containing all observations in a dataset. In practice, though, you’ll want to have at least a training and validation split. The easiest way to get these is to randomly split your data container into two parts. Here we split
into 80% training and 20% validation data. Note the use of
to make sure each split has approximately the same class distribution.

children: This is great for experimenting, but where possible you will want to use the official training/validation split for a dataset. Consider the image classification dataset folder structure:

- $dir
    - train
        - class1
            - image1.jpg
            - image2.jpg
            - ...
        - class2
        - ...
    - valid
        - class1
        - class2
        - ...
As you can see, the grandparent folder of each image indicates which split it is a part of.
allows us to partition a data container using a function. Let’s use it to split
based on the name of the grandparent directory. (We can’t reuse
for this since it no longer carries the file information.)
Using this official split, it will be easier to compare the performance of your results with those of others’.
